    "pageContentHtml": "<p><strong>BLURB</strong>: We assume no prior familiarity with AI and we will not become experts overnight.  But let&#39;s get the lay of the land and a foundational understanding of the main concepts.  In class, we&#39;ll turn ourselves into a human neural network to illustrate how these things work. PostClass we train and share a <a href=\"https://teachablemachine.withgoogle.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Teachable Machine Model.</a>\n<a href=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia2025-ai-bootcamp/edit\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">EDIT SLIDES</a></p>\n<iframe src=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia2025-ai-bootcamp/embed?style=light&byline=hidden&share=hidden&shared_notes=hidden\" width=\"576\" height=\"420\" title=\"HMIA 2025 AI Bootcamp\" scrolling=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>\n## What is AI?\n\n<p>Artificial intelligence refers to systems designed to perform tasks that typically require human intelligence.</p>\n<p>From neurons to alignment. Lecture+hands on exercises (teachable machine?) that help us to understand (1) artificial neurons (2) training (3) deployment.  PreClass Work is 2 MIT videos + Hero + BlueBrown + StopThink Qs plus flashcards. Lecture is neuron+weights+training+visual data through perceptron Activity is an embodied neural network for guessing M&amp;M&#39;s in jars. Intro to teachable machine. PostClass Work is train and share a Teachable Machine Model</p>\n<h2>Key Concepts</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Machine Learning</strong>: Systems that learn from data</li>\n<li><strong>Neural Networks</strong>: Architectures inspired by biological neurons</li>\n<li><strong>Large Language Models</strong>: Text prediction at scale</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Discussion</h2>\n<p>What distinguishes &quot;intelligence&quot; from sophisticated pattern matching?</p>\n",
