    "pageContentHtml": "<p><strong>BLURB</strong>: Reading hard papers is hard, especially when we venture beyond our home intellectual territory.  We will absorb the wisdom of two teachers who have thought about how to teach this skill, S Keshav of the University of Waterloo and V, Bengston of the University of Southern California. Then we will apply these methods to a paper that will be central to the rest of the course. <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1606.06565\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Almodei et al. 2016 Concrete Problems in AI Safety</a>.  PostClass we extract some core ideas from the paper and create our first set of &quot;alignment cards.&quot;\n<a href=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia2025-how-to-read-hard-stuff/edit\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">EDIT SLIDES</a><iframe src=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia2025-how-to-read-hard-stuff/embed?style=light&byline=hidden&share=hidden&shared_notes=hidden\" width=\"576\" height=\"420\" title=\"HMIA 2025 How to Read Hard Stuff\" scrolling=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>\nPreClass Work is reading Bengston and Keshav and taking a first look (what Bengston calls &quot;survey&quot; and &quot;query&quot;) Amodei, et al.  There are also some flashcards for &quot;memorizing&quot; Amodei&#39;s five concrete problems.</p>\n<p>In class, we will talk about the two techniques and apply them to the paper together. NOTE: deck now includes my slides from BI orientation - they need to be thinned out.</p>\n<p>Assignment One (in PostClass Work): Analogize each of five problems to familiar context and then rewrite the final conclusion paragraph of Amodei et al. paper.</p>\n",
