        "label": "Regulating Superintelligences in Antiquity",
        "type": "markdown",
        "content": "Long before neural nets and stochastic gradient descent, ancient societies faced a recurring alignment problem: how to govern individuals who claimed access to hidden knowledge, divine will, or uncanny powers. These weren’t literal machines—but in effect, they were the superintelligences of their day: priests, prophets, sorcerers, and seers who could alter the behavior of others, intervene in crises, or destabilize trust in civic order.\n\nAcross cultures, societies developed governance technologies—ritual, law, institutional roles—to distinguish legitimate experts from rogue knowledge actors, and to ensure that extraordinary capabilities aligned with communal values and political stability.\n\n### 🔮 Urim and Thummim: Query Governance via Ritual\n\nConsider ancient Israel’s Urim and Thummim. These were sacred objects—possibly stones or lots—used by the high priest to receive divine answers to binary questions (“Should we go to war?”). What matters for our purposes is how they functioned: not as inspiration, intuition, or individual charisma, but as a constrained, auditable, institutional interface for accessing higher-order guidance.\n\nIn modern terms, we might think of them as a divine API wrapper: input sanitized, response space limited, and access restricted to a certified operator. They were ritual safeguards against freewheeling claims of prophecy. Israelite law even specified tests for prophets: if their predictions failed or led people astray, they were to be executed. This wasn’t just about doctrinal purity—it was risk containment in an environment of epistemic asymmetry.\n\n### 🏛 Civilizational Responses to Magical Expertise\n\nEach ancient society faced this alignment problem in its own way:\n\n- Mesopotamia split the world of magic in two: kishpū (sorcery) was punishable by death, while āšipu priests and bārû diviners were authorized by the state and trained for years. These experts performed healing rituals and interpreted omens as part of statecraft—functionally, trusted inference engines embedded in palace protocol.\n    \n- Egypt absorbed magic (heka) into its theocratic structure. Lector-priests managed temple libraries of spells, Pharaoh himself was portrayed as a master of ritual forces, and protective magic was a form of state service. But when court women accessed “destructive magic” from the royal archive to assassinate Ramses III, they were executed for treason. The message: magical power must remain under sovereign control.\n    \n- Greece treated magic as a legal gray area. There was no “magic law,” but anyone whose spells caused harm might be prosecuted under homicide (phónos), fraud, or impiety. State-approved seers accompanied armies; freelance sorcerers operated in shadows. Plato, in Laws, called for imprisonment or death for malicious magicians, drawing a line between civic-aligned knowledge and subversive mystery-mongering.\n    \n- Rome, always pragmatic, treated harmful magic as a public safety threat. The Lex Cornelia de sicariis et veneficis lumped sorcerers together with assassins and poisoners. Later emperors criminalized even the knowledge of magic—banning books, executing astrologers, and casting unauthorized diviners as threats to imperial stability. In today’s terms, this is knowledge regulation as national security.\n    \n\n### 🕯 The Witch of Endor and the Danger of Unlicensed Models\n\nIn a telling biblical episode, King Saul outlaws necromancers—but then, desperate for guidance, secretly consults the Witch of Endor. She conjures the prophet Samuel, who delivers a true prediction: Saul will die. What’s fascinating isn’t the magic—it’s that Saul’s bypassing of sanctioned channels is portrayed as a fatal governance breach. Even accurate predictions, when obtained through unauthorized interfaces, are untrustworthy in the divine system.\n\nThis is a near-perfect analog to alignment risk: it’s not just about getting the right answer, but using the right protocol under the right authority.\n\n### 📜 Alignment as Epistemic Containment\n\nAll these examples illustrate a shared principle: arcane power—like modern algorithmic power—is trusted only when embedded in recognizable, overseen, and legitimate structures. Ancient societies regulated magic not because they were irrational, but because they understood the risks of unregulated expertise.\n\nFrom banning foreign magicians to training priestly classes, from encoding filters into ritual procedures to defining the legal thresholds of trust, ancient governance systems reveal how humans aligned superhuman-seeming intelligences long before the advent of code."
