    "pageContentHtml": "<p><strong>BLURB</strong>: One explanation for how humans manage alignment with one another and their communities is that they &quot;share meaning&quot; - that my ideas are not all MY ideas but rather they match and mirror the ideas of people around me.  This is the basic idea that we can coordinate because we have &quot;shared values.&quot;  The question this raises for social science is where does shared meaning come from?  We&#39;ll start by reading a short selection from Karl Marx called &quot;The Production of Consciousness.&quot; \n<a href=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia-2025-shared-meaning/edit\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">EDIT SLIDES</a><iframe src=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia-2025-shared-meaning/embed?style=light&byline=hidden&share=hidden\" width=\"576\" height=\"420\" title=\"HMIA 2025 Shared Meaning\" scrolling=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>\nHow Humans Achieve Cooperation and Coordination through Shared Meaning (humans, organizations, experts, machines)</p>\n<p>One explanation for how humans manage alignment with one another and their communities is that they &quot;share meaning&quot; - that my ideas are not all MY ideas but rather they match and mirror the ideas of people around me.  This is the basic idea that we can coordinate because we have &quot;shared values.&quot;  The question this raises for social science is where does shared meaning come from?  We&#39;ll start by reading a short selection from Karl Marx called &quot;The Production of Consciousness.&quot;  Then we&#39;ll turn to George Herbert Mead who has a theory of the &quot;generalized other&quot; - a model we have in our heads of how the rest of the world will react to things we consider doing or saying. The models that Marx and Mead describe give us some sense of how a person can be dropped down in a new social environment and figure out what the rules are.  A question for AI alignment is whether something like that can be done with machine intelligence.  We will read a relatively simple technical paper about trying to teach AI values by having them watch humans and trying to learn values from them.</p>\n<h1>How Humans Do It: Shared Meaning</h1>\n<h2>How Humans Do It: Shared Meaning</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What are the failure modes of shared culture/meaning? Failures&quot; as analogous to market failures?  </li>\n<li>What are the analogies?</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In our last conversation we raised the question: are principles really enough? Today we want to assume that they are and ask how would that work?</p>\n<p>If principles and their adoption as values are going to work as alignment mechanisms we need to clarify how these get &quot;into&quot; humans, organizations, experts, and machines and how they function as guides to behavior.</p>\n<p>HINT HINT There needs to be this prior commitment to living up to principles or there has to be integrity in acting in accordance with one&#39;s values or there has to be a built in desire to &quot;do the right thing&quot; (and the principles provide an answer to what is the right thing).</p>\n<p>So, today we are asking the question: how do humans lay a foundation for the capacity to live by principles in a way that can produce alignment.</p>\n<p>First though we want to establish an analogy that can be useful.</p>\n<p>Let&#39;s review some basics of reinforcement learning. In reinforcement learning, we imagine an agent (like a robot) moving through different situations (called <strong>states</strong>) and choosing <strong>actions</strong>. After each action, the agent gets some feedback in the form of a number — a <strong>reward</strong> — that tells it how good or bad that action turned out to be. Over time, with experience, the agent can discover a <strong>policy</strong>, which is just a rule for what action to take in each situation, so that it can maximize its total reward in the long run.</p>\n<p>A reward function maps actions and situations to an evaluation - how good or bad is that action in that situation. This is precisely the &quot;taking things into account&quot; that came up in our Q&amp;A.</p>\n<p>Formally a policy is a function that maps states (situations) to actions.</p>\n<p>Our ethical concerns about humans, organizations, experts, and machines have something in common: we expect/hope that in any given situation, they will decide to do what is right.  </p>\n<p>When we articulate a set of ethical guidelines or principles, the primary mechanism by which we think this can work to align behavior is that the agent has some prior or innate commitment to &quot;do what is right.&quot; The principles then provide a classification in any given situation as to what action is &quot;most right.&quot; In another context we might say the principle provides a warrant - something we can reference to claim that some action is the most right action in the situation.</p>\n<p>By analogy to machine learning, we say the agent has a policy. The policy indicates what the agent will do in any given situation (state). The policy is ethical (and the agent morally aligned) if its action choices align with the principles. If a principle guides an agent&#39;s policy then we say that the agent has that principle as a value. </p>\n<p>A policy emerges by the application of a &quot;reward function&quot; to the consideration of different actions in any given situation (state).  In practice, the policy is a learned approximation to the optimization implied by those values.  So, by analogy, the principles are features of the reward function. In ML terms, the reward function encodes what the agent hopes to achieve. What we are saying is that in an ethically aligned agent principles are dominant features of the reward function - in other words, pure pleasure might also be a feature of my reward function, but my integrity can outweigh pursuit of pleasure.</p>\n<p>At least three things are necessary for this to work. One is that the principles need to be &quot;right&quot; and consistent enough and complete enough to be useful as guides.  Two, the agents have to be referencing something like the same set of principles. And three, the agents have to have a mechanism for living up to the principles.</p>\n<p>INVERSE RL. In humans the reward function is partly learned from experience and partly inferred based on the behavior of others.</p>\n",
