    "pageContentHtml": "<h1>Transparency and Record Keeping</h1>\n<p><strong>BLURB</strong>: One of the super powers of bureaucracy is record keeping. One of the super powers of democracy is transparency. Do they have a more general application?\n<a href=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia2025-recordkeeping/edit\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">SLIDES</a></p>\n<iframe src=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia2025-recordkeeping/embed?style=light&byline=hidden&share=hidden\" width=\"576\" height=\"420\" title=\"HMIA 2025 Transparency and Record Keeping\" scrolling=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>\nReadings  \n  1. \"[The Checklist](https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/12/10/the-checklist)\" by Atul Gawande The New Yorker December 2, 2007  \n2. Book The Checklist Manifesto [on Internet Archive](https://ia601306.us.archive.org/6/items/TheChecklistManifesto/AtulGawandeTheChecklistManifestoHowToGetThingsRight2010.pdf)  \n3. Chapter 2 from The Checklist Manifesto \"The Checklist\" pp. 32-47.  \n4. Chapter 4 from The Checklist Manifesto “The Idea” pp 72-85  \n5. Review pages from Perrow on Weber's bureaucracy and Weber himself on recordkeeping([in FILES](https://jhu.instructure.com/courses/104047/files?preview=14876410)).  \n6. The Shuttle Inquiry ([NYT pdf in FILES](https://jhu.instructure.com/courses/104047/files/folder/Full%20Text?preview=14774084))  \n7. Sections on auditing in Data and Society [Algorithmic Accountability](https://datasociety.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/DandS_Algorithmic_Accountability.pdf) 2018  \n8. Metaxa et al. 2021 \"[Auditing Algorithms](https://hci.stanford.edu/publications/2021/FnT_AuditingAlgorithms.pdf) Foundations and Trends® in Human-Computer Interaction: Vol. 14, No. 4, pp 272–344. DOI: 10.1561/1100000083. Sections 1.1 What is an audit? 1.2 Differentiating Algorithm Audits from Other Testing 3.1 What is an Algorithm Audit? 3.2 Algorithm Auditing Domains  \n9. Ryan Notification Norms  \n10. [AMA Opinion 1.1.6](https://coe-dev.ama-assn.org/sites/amacoedb/files/2022-08/1.1.6%20Quality%20--%20background%20reports.pdf) suggests responsibility to monitor self and others for quality.  \nClass: Think about a time when things went badly because there were no records. Think about a time where you were saved by the fact that there was a written record. Concepts: records, audits, reporting requirements. Notification norms. Target insight: why do we expect record keeping and audits and transparency to promote alignment in each of our realms.",
