        "label": "Alignment by Structures & Institutional Design",
        "type": "markdown",
        "content": "BLURB: Structural and institutional design refers to things that distribute, constrain, and audit power. Rooted in a long tradition of political and institutional design, these mechanisms treat power as natural and inherently fallible and alignment as structurally fragile. Their goal is not to make agents more virtuous or governable or to specify acceptable and unacceptable behaviors, but to make systems of agents alignable even when agents fail.\n## Structures and Institutional Design\n[EDIT SLIDES](https://slides.com/djjr/hmia2025-structures-and-institutional-design/edit)<iframe src=\"https://slides.com/djjr/hmia2025-structures-and-institutional-design/embed?style=light&byline=hidden&share=hidden\" width=\"576\" height=\"420\" title=\"HMIA 2025 Structures and Institutional Design\" scrolling=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>\n\nGIST: Structural and institutional design refers to things that distribute, constrain, and audit power. Rooted in a long tradition of political and institutional design, these mechanisms treat power as natural and inherently fallible and alignment as structurally fragile. Their goal is not to make agents more virtuous or governable or to specify acceptable and unacceptable behaviors, but to make systems of agents alignable even when agents fail. By embedding guardrails against capture, drift, and corruption, these structural patterns  preserve the conditions for accountable, resilient behavior.  \n    26. READINGS  \n        1. Alexander Hamilton [Federalist 51](https://jhu.instructure.com/courses/104047/files/folder/Full%20Text?preview=14877725) ([online National Archives](https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Hamilton/01-04-02-0199)) ([short excerpt](https://www.gilderlehrman.org/sites/default/files/inline-pdfs/opposingviewpoints.handouts2.pdf))  \n           2. Madison explains and defends the checks and balances system. Each branch of government is framed so that its power checks the power of the other two branches and each branch of government is dependent on the people, who are the source of legitimate authority. Madison also shows how republican government can serve as a check on the power of factions, and the tyranny of the majority.  Checks and balances preserve liberty by ensuring justice: “Justice is the end of government. It is the end of civil society.” Madison’s political theory here shows the influence of [Montesquieu’s *The Spirit of the Laws*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Spirit_of_Law).  \n        3. Williams J 2018 \"[Elinor Ostrom’s 8 rules for managing the commons](https://earthbound.report/2018/01/15/elinor-ostroms-8-rules-for-managing-the-commons/)\" (blog post)  \n        4. Ostrom E 1990 Governing the Commons ([PDF](https://www.actu-environnement.com/media/pdf/ostrom_1990.pdf)) see chapter 1  \n        5. Ostrom E 1990 [Nobel Prize Address](https://www.nobelprize.org/uploads/2018/06/ostrom_lecture.pdf)  \n        6. Lessig, L 2000 \"Code is Law\" ([Harvard Magazine](https://www.harvardmagazine.com/2000/01/code-is-law-html))   \n        7. Olson M 1965 The Logic of Collective Action ([short excerpt from chapter 1](https://jhu.instructure.com/courses/104047/files/folder/Full%20Text?preview=14877801))  \n        8. Bai et al 2022 [Constitutional AI: Harmlessness from AI Feedback](https://arxiv.org/abs/2212.08073)  \n        9. Hannah Arendt – On Revolution, Chapter 5: “The Revolutionary Tradition and Its Lost Treasure” (in aPDF4DJR \\- needs to be processed if used)  \n        10. [Wikipedia Governance](https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia_Governance_\\(2002_essay\\)) (2002)  \n        11. [WikipediA:Administration](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Administration)"
