    "pageContentHtml": "<h2>Safety</h2>\n<p><strong>BLURB</strong>: &quot;Safety&quot; is so obvious that it can be hard to define. But we use it a lot to align intelligences.</p>\n<h4>Readings</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Gawande 2007 <a href=\"https://psnet.ahrq.gov/perspective/conversation-withatul-gawande-md-ma-mph\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">In Conversation with</a> (safety and MMconferences)  </li>\n<li>Vinay Prasad. 2010 <a href=\"https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55550f38e4b0884d8d80118e/t/5565d6b7e4b0c52cdcc600a1/1432737463486/2010+-+July+-+Medical+Humanities+-+Reclaiming+the+Morbidity+and+Mortality+Conference.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Reclaiming the morbidity and mortality conference: between Codman and Kundera</a>  </li>\n<li>Haynes, et al. 2009 <a href=\"https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsa0810119\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">A Surgical Safety Checklist to Reduce Morbidity and Morality in a Global Population</a> New England Journal of Medicine 8pp</li>\n</ol>\n",
