    "pageContentHtml": "<p><strong>BLURB</strong>: Norbert Wiener (1894–1964) invented the field of cybernetics, which he described as “the science of communication as it relates to living things and machines” — but which we now often understand as the science of control.  In this session, we’ll close out our semester by reading and reflecting on his writing about purpose, feedback, error correction, system fragility, and the ethical dangers of optimization without alignment. Wiener is the author of what may be the original alignment warning — a quote as relevant to AI today as it was to missiles in 1947: “If we use, to achieve our purposes, a mechanical agency with whose operation we cannot efficiently interfere… then we had better be quite sure that the purpose put into the machine is the purpose which we really desire and not merely a colorful imitation of it.”\nConversations with Our Father: Norbert Wiener and Our Future</p>\n<p>GIST: Norbert Wiener (1894–1964) invented the field of cybernetics, which he described as “the science of communication as it relates to living things and machines” — but which we now often understand as the science of control.</p>\n<p>He can legitimately be credited with the core insight that grounds this course: that all intelligent behavior arises from feedback mechanisms, and that this makes possible deep commonalities across intelligences — human, organizational, expert, and machine.</p>\n<p>During World War II, Wiener worked on the deeply practical and morally fraught problem of how to assist and automate anti-aircraft guns — a context that forced him to think precisely about goal-seeking, feedback, and control under uncertainty.</p>\n<p>In this session, we’ll read and reflect on his writing about purpose, feedback, error correction, system fragility, and the ethical dangers of optimization without alignment. Wiener is the author of what may be the original alignment warning — a quote as relevant to AI today as it was to missiles in 1947:</p>\n<p>“If we use, to achieve our purposes, a mechanical agency with whose operation we cannot efficiently interfere… then we had better be quite sure that the purpose put into the machine is the purpose which we really desire and not merely a colorful imitation of it.”  </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Reading  </li>\n<li>Norbert Wiener – The Human Use of Human Beings (1950, rev. 1954) [<a href=\"https://archive.org/details/humanuseofhumanb00wien\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Internet Archive</a>][<a href=\"https://monoskop.org/images/6/60/Wiener_Norbert_The_Human_Use_of_Human_Beings_1989.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Online PDF</a>][<a href=\"https://monoskop.org/images/9/90/Wiener_Norbert_The_Human_Use_of_Human_Beings_1950.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Online PDF</a>] (these chapter cites likely not quite right. see <a href=\"https://jhu.instructure.com/courses/104047/pages/wiener-1954-the-human-use-of-human-beings\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">canvas page</a> (which still is incomplete) summarizing chapters and correct the items below.  </li>\n<li>Chapter 2: “Progress and Entropy”  </li>\n<li>Chapter 1: “Cybernetics in History”  </li>\n<li>Chapter 11?: “Man and Machine”  </li>\n<li>Discussion  </li>\n<li>Ch 2. Systems tend toward disorder unless maintained via feedback and purpose; cybernetic systems maintain order by exchanging information with environment<br>Q: if all systems tend toward entropy, what does this say about the fragility of alignment and the efforts and mechanisms needed to maintain it? [alignment as ongoing task, need for constant feedback to avoid drift]  </li>\n<li>Ch 1. Feedback-based control is not new. Evolutionary history. Human history. Mechanical history.<br>Q: Wiener claims that feedback is a universal feature of purposeful systems. If that’s true, what kinds of feedback do alignment mechanisms need to make systems governable across different domains — human, organizational, professional, machine? [connect alignment mechanism categories to feedback - and what is effect of noise?]  </li>\n<li>Ch 11?. What if goals are mis-designed or poorly aligned?<br>Q: Wiener warns that we must ensure the purpose we give a machine is the one we truly desire. Is this still the central problem of AI alignment today — or have the challenges shifted? What about the other problems of alignment? [let&#39;s get diagnostic - are goals the problem or oversight, incentives, socio-economic embedding]  </li>\n<li>Bonus Q: How much alignment can you get from feedback and control alone — and where do you need ethics, law, or structure?  </li>\n<li><a href=\"https://chatgpt.com/share/e/6885b1ed-553c-8008-ad68-82309b54d53e\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Readings for syllabus</a> has some exercise ideas at the end.</li>\n</ol>\n",
